		</ul>
	</section>
<!-- e ferd/hearst/templates/premium/article/content/related-links.tpl -->
                                                                	<p>It was a dangerous situation, too. Only a few years earlier San Francisco had seen an outbreak of bubonic plague, spread mostly by rats. One hundred nineteen people in the city died in that epidemic.</p>


                                                                	<p>Torney ran what was called the Sanitary Commision for weeks until the civilian authorities took over.</p>


                                                                	<p>There is a passage about Torney in the official history of the Army Medical Corps. &ldquo;He acquitted himself very well in the face of the greatest difficulties,&rdquo; it said. Torney&rsquo;s record, the army said, was &ldquo;brilliant,&rdquo; and he was promoted to full colonel and later brigadier general. He was reassigned to Washington, D.C., named surgeon general of the United States Army, and dined at the White House with President Theodore Roosevelt.</p>


                                                                	
                                                                	<p>Richard Torney, a Marin historian, likes to remind people about his great great grandfather, especially around the earthquake anniversary. &ldquo;I&rsquo;d say he played a major unsung role in the aftermath of the earthquake,&rdquo; he said.</p>


                                                                	<p>The only reminder of Torney&rsquo;s role is a small street in the Presidio. But there is nothing to remind us of the black families who stood on Sacramento Street and watched their city burn.</p>


                                                                	<p>Perhaps we can remember these San Franciscans on April 18 while staying at home. We don&rsquo;t need to create a new disaster on the anniversary of an old one.</p>


                                                                	<em><p>Carl Nolte is a San Francisco Chronicle staff writer. Email: <a href="mailto:cnolte@sfchronicle.com" title="cnolte@sfchronicle.com">cnolte@sfchronicle.com</a> Twitter: <a href="https://twitter.com/CarlnolteSF" title="@CarlnolteSF">@CarlnolteSF</a></p></em>


                            </section>
